    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "ok i think i get that part. but so if the p-value is low, it's basically just saying the results weren't just a random fluke or chance happening? like how do researchers actually account for that randomness in the data?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Researchers use statistical methods to assess whether the observed results are likely due to chance. The p-value is one aspect of this, measuring the probability of obtaining the results by chance alone. By looking at large samples and repeating the study (e.g., through meta-analysis), researchers can further reduce the chance of a \"random fluke.\" Additionally, statisticians use techniques like hypothesis testing, confidence intervals, and effect size calculations to help interpret the p-value and quantify the real effect of the treatment.",
      "source": "target",
